{{wikipedia}}

==English==
===Etymology===
[[English]]: '''[[star]]''' + [[past participle]] of the verb '''to [[cross]]'''

First attested [[w:1592|1592]], from "[[w:Romeo and Juliet|Romeo and Juliet]]" by [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]] ([[w:1564|1564]]-[[w:1616|1616]]):
:''"From out the fatal loins of those two foes
:''A pair of [[star-crossed]] lovers take their life."'' &mdash; '''Romeo and Juliet''', ''Prologue''

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈstɑ ˌkrɒst/}} {{italbrac|[[RP]]}}
*{{IPA|/ˈstɑːr ˌkrɑst/}} {{italbrac|US}}

===Adjective===
'''star-crossed'''

#[[ill]]-[[fated]] by [[destiny]], the [[fate]] of the person being "written in the stars".
#:''The '''star-crossed''' lovers looked into each other's eyes, before dying.''
::Note: commonly [[misconstrued]] as ''to be in love''

